<TEXT>
an experimental device that takes pictures 
inside blood vessels was used on people for the first time and one 
of its developers sees significant applications for it 
i had two patients today watching us do it dr christopher 
white said wednesday they kept telling me turn the tv so i can 
see it doc 
we had to explain that it was important for us to see the tv 
and wed show them the videotape later 
ochsner medical institutions a suburban new orleans hospital 
that hired white and his partner dr stephen ramee after they got 
out of the army in july is the first to start clinical trials of 
their gadet the percutaneous coronary angioscope 
its of great interest to be able to see the inside of the 
coronary arteries from the outside of the patient so this type of 
device may have important application said dr albert raizner 
director of the cardiac catheterization laboratory at the methodist 
hospital in houston and an associate professor at baylor college of 
medicine 
the machine made by advanced cardiovascular systems of mountain 
view calif has been approved for trial by the food and drug 
administration at four other hospitals white said those tests are 
expected to start in the next few months 
fiber optics have been used for at least a decade to look into 
the digestive tract but it was only in recent years that optical 
fibers became small enough to use in blood vessels 
white said the angioscope which he ramee and engineer tom doyle 
designed is smaller than those already on the market so it can get 
into smaller arteries 
its a triple tube of plastic less than onequarter inch wide 
one section holds 2000 extremely thin optical fibers in a bundle 
smaller in circumference than pencil lead a second hollow tube 
carries medicine or saline solution the third holds a tiny balloon 
of the sort now used to flatten cholesterol plaques in a procedure 
called balloon angioplasty 
an xray guidance system is used to route the triple tube from a 
blood vessel at the top of the leg toward the heart once its 
where doctors want it the balloon is filled with liquid and a tiny 
amount of saline may be pumped in to clear away the opaque blood 
that is one of the major refinements of his machine white said 
several japanese machines are on the market he said but they rely 
on flushing salt water through the arteries to clear away the blood 
if the device proves as safe as he expects it could be used to 
see whether a blood clot cholesterol plaque or spasm in an artery 
is causing a heart attack white said each is treated differently 
and doctors cant be certain which treatment should be used he 
said 
it also would let doctors drip medicine to dissolve the clot 
precisely at the spot it was needed and stop the drip as soon as 
the clot disappeared he said 
</TEXT>
