<TEXT>
sen edward kennedy says his legislation to 
require employers to provide health insurance for workers has a 
better chance for passage this year because the plight of the 37 
million uninsured has received so much attention 
my sense is the country is prepared to come to grips on 
this the massachusetts democrat said wednesday theres a 
great deal of anxiety among the american people 
last year legislation sponsored by kennedy in the senate and 
rep henry waxman dcalif in the house was met with strong 
opposition in the business community and went nowhere the senate 
labor and human resources committee which kennedy chairs approved 
the measure but it never got to the floor in the house it never 
got out of committee 
kennedy and waxman announced new legislation on wednesday that 
builds on last years bill incorporating provisions requiring 
employers to provide health insurance for workers and phasing in an 
expansion of the medicaid program to cover the nonworking poor 
the measure they say will provide health insurance to all 
americans by 1999 
kennedy estimated the federal cost of the medicaid expansion at 
about 5 billion over 10 years and states would have to match the 
federal contribution businesses would face about 18 billion in 
new costs but subsidies and lowercost insurance pools would be 
available to help small businesses 
benefits would be essentially the same as the basic package 
employers would be required to offer including physician services 
hospital services diagnostic tests pregnancy and wellbaby care 
and a limited mental health benefit under the measure 
the measure has been endorsed by 100 organizations representing 
organized labor health care providers women consumers and 
religious groups however businesses are expected to oppose the 
bill as they did last year 
an estimated 24 million of the americans without health 
insurance are members of working families and would be covered 
under the kennedywaxman bill employers would be required to 
provide the basic package of benefits to employees working more 
than 17 hours per week and to their families 
the bill sets limits on copayments deductibles and the 
employee share of the premiums and provides coverage for 
catastrophic illness it also would not allow anyone to be denied 
insurance because of an existing medical condition 
addressing some of the concerns that were raised last year 
kennedy rejected arguments that it would hurt businesses 
economically and the country competitively 
in fact the legislation will help not harm american 
businesses in world markets he said most of the manufacturing 
companies involved in international trade already provide insurance 
for their workers but these businesses pay too much for health 
insurance because others pay too little he said 
waxman added what we need to do is spread the cost of 
covering workers across all employers and spread the risk of 
illness fairly among insurance companies 
for those not eligible for jobbased insurance the medicaid 
program would be expanded gradually beginning in 1991 with the 6 
million uninsured poor americans not now eligible for the 
federalstate insurance program 
the second phase would begin in 1996 and include the near poor 
whose income are within 185 percent of the poverty line these 
people would pay a share of the cost of their coverage 
a final phase would begin in 1999 to cover the remaining 
uninsured 
</TEXT>
