<TEXT>
a consumer advocate says the outlook for the 
1989 harvest is so grim that the government should suspend export 
subsidies despite their popularity with wheat farmers 
rodney e leonard executive director of the private nonprofit 
community nutrition institute said wednesday he wrote agriculture 
secretary clayton yeutter on april 3 to repeat a similar request 
made last fall when the situation was less precarious and 
steps could have been taken to safeguard supplies 
the institute studies nutrition and food policy issues 
the target of leonards complaint is the export enhancement 
program or eep which subsidizes the sale of wheat and other 
commodities to selected foreign countries huge sales of wheat to 
china and the soviet union have been made under the program since 
the arrangement was authorized by congress in the 1985 farm law 
subsidies at one time ranged to more than 40 per metric ton or 
approximately 109 per bushel from less than 20 per ton or 
about 54 cents per bushel lately reflecting generally higher 
world prices the subsidies have been even lower with shipments to 
china recently carrying eep subsidies of 633 per ton or 17 cents 
per bushel 
a metric ton is about 2205 pounds and is equal to 367 bushels 
of wheat 
yeutter said this week the program had helped significantly in 
getting agricultural trade discussions moving under the current 
uruguay round of the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
but yeutter also said in an interview with a group of reporters 
on monday that the subsidy program would be reviewed to see how 
effective it has been and whether too much or too little is 
being spent on it 
leonard said that the condition of the winter wheat crop is 
deteriorating and that experts in the agriculture department and in 
the major production areas point to a harvest this year of about 
16 billion bushels a spring wheat output of 600 million bushels 
would make a total us wheat harvest of about 22 billion bushels 
if wheat use in the 198990 marketing year which will begin 
june 1 totals in the range of 24 billion to 25 billion bushels 
this years harvest would fall short of meeting demand 
in that case leonard said in his letter to yeutter at least 
200 million bushels of wheat will have to be drawn from existing 
stocks which are estimated by the agriculture department to be 
drawn down to 549 million bushels by june 1 
thus he said the us wheat stockpile by june 1 1990 could 
well be down to around 300 million bushels according to department 
records that would be the the smallest us wheat reserve at the 
end of a marketing year since 1952 when it was 256 million bushels 
this is hardly adequate as a domestic reserve and will leave 
the us unable to intervene if famine conditions develop anywhere 
in the world leonard said the united nations food and 
agriculture organization a month ago said that world grain 
stocks will be drawn down again in 198990 for the third year in a 
row 
leonard added in effect fao does not expect food grain 
production to increase significantly in any of the major 
foodproducing areas outside the us 
the departments first official estimate of 1989 winter wheat 
production which usually accounts for threefourths of the us 
total will be released may 11 
meanwhile department analysts have used unofficial projections 
showing that the 1989 wheat harvest could be as low as 23 billion 
bushels or slightly more than leonards benchmark 
the biggest problem is in major areas of the great plains 
particularly in kansas the no 1 wheat producer where soils have 
been parched since the crop was planted last fall 
yeutter is scheduled to tour some of the kansas wheat area on 
friday his office said there has been congressional pressure on 
the department to extend 1988 drought relief to the stricken winter 
wheat farmers 
</TEXT>
