<TEXT>
president bushs proposal to ban campaign 
contributions by political action committees is one of those offers 
that sounds great politicians forgoing money in the name of good 
government 
and special interest money at that as the political action 
committees have become known 
his motive however is probably not so pure the fact is 
bushs proposal reflects the growing recognition among republicans 
that the system of contributions by political action committees has 
backfired on the party 
it is primarily congressional incumbents who are benefiting from 
the pac contributions and because more incumbents are democrats 
than republicans democrats are getting the bigger share of the 
money 
bush proposed doing away with the pac contributions in effect 
doing away with the pacs at a meeting of the american society of 
newspaper editors in washington on wednesday he offered the 
suggestion as he released a broader ethics package designed to 
tighten rules for congress judges and the executive branch 
pacs weaken the parties restrain competition and deaden the 
political debate bush said 
political action committees are one of the products of the 
postwatergate campaign reforms and are a prime example of the law 
of unintended consequences 
they are a multimilliondollar enterprise that virtually no one 
is happy with critics say they skew the political system in favor 
of the narrow interests they represent and make incumbents even 
harder to dislodge from office 
the pacs are committees organized around officers and employees 
of corporations businesses trade associations and the like whose 
members make contributions that are collected together and donated 
to candidates 
republicans originally saw the pacs as a businessoriented 
republican answer to the contributions democrats were getting from 
labor unions 
as the amounts of money have grown in politics so have the 
pacs in the 1988 election cycle according to the federal election 
commission pacs contributed more than 151 million to house and 
senate candidates a decade earlier their contributions totaled 
onefifth that 
with their growth however has come an unmistakable trend the 
pac managers increasingly have decided that rather than providing 
campaign contributions to challengers with whom they might share 
some views and who often are badly in need of money theyd rather 
put their money on the candidate who is more likely to win 
in nearly all cases thats an incumbent 
and the pacs tend to favor the committee chairmen and 
subcommittee chairmen who are entrenched in office and have power 
over their areas of interest 
in 1988 incumbents got 118 million of the pac contributions 
challengers got less than 19 million the rest went to candidates 
for open seats 
for democratic candidates for the house and senate pacs made 
close to 99 million in contributions for republicans there was 
less than 61 million 
pacs can give up to 5000 per election to a candidate but can 
spend unlimited amounts on their own in a candidates behalf 
and who were the top recipients last year in the house it was 
democrat richard gephardt one of the presidential hopefuls and 
hardly an endangered candidate in his house reelection battle in 
the senate it was texas sen lloyd bentsen the democratic vice 
presidential nominee who easily won reelection to the senate 
doing away with pacs has support among democrats too but many 
democrats want to do so as part of a bigger move to public 
financing of congressional campaigns just as the presidential 
general election campaign is financed with taxpayer money 
bush said he opposed public financing 
many republicans have been advocating an alternative that would 
be more to their liking instead of providing public financing 
they would strengthen the role of the parties by lifting the limits 
on individual contributions to the political parties 
individuals can now give no more than 1000 per election to a 
candidate but they can give 20000 annually to a party and 
advocates of this plan would like to see even larger amounts 
bush didnt add that idea to his proposal to the editors but he 
suggested it 
modern democratic government works best when organized by 
strong political parties and yet we have allowed our parties to 
become weakened and overshadowed by special interests bush said 
and we can best restore the role of the parties by limiting 
political action committees 
small wonder he would want to see more influence for the 
parties contributions to the republican party and its house and 
senate campaign committees regularly dwarf those going to the 
democratic counterparts the republicans easily raise four or five 
times what the democrats raise in this type of contribution and 
the republicans had a 100 million lead over the democrats in 1984 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
editors note william m welch has covered the last two 
presidential elections for the associated press 
</TEXT>
