<TEXT>
john christian warner a chemist who played an 
important role in developing the atomic bomb and who served as 
president of the former carnegie institute of technology for 15 
years has died at age 91 
he died in his sleep wednesday at the suburban retirement center 
where he lived 
warner who began his education in a oneroom school in indiana 
joined carnegie tech now carnegiemellon university in 1926 as a 
chemistry instructor 
he was head of the chemistry department in 1938 and 1949 and 
dean of graduate studies from 1945 to 1949 
warner became president of carnegie tech in 1950 his 
administration pioneered the use of computers in education 
establishing a computation center in 1956 that helped the 
institution gain national recognition as a center of research in 
computer science 
during the last two years of world war ii warner worked on the 
manhattan project supervising research on the chemistry and 
metallurgy of plutonium he was on the general advisory committee 
to the us atomic energy commission for 12 years and also served 
on the policy advisory board of the argonne national laboratory 
warner was technical assistant to the 1958 un international 
conference on peaceful uses of atomic energy he was chairman of 
the organizing committee and first president of the universities 
research association and designer builder and operator of the 
united states most powerful particle accelerator in the fermi 
laboratory in batavia ill 
he is survived by two sons three grandchildren and four 
greatgrandchildren 
</TEXT>
