<TEXT>
pal maleter a 39yearold hungarian 
general told his wife that his countrymen desperately needed him 
during their uprising against the soviets in 1956 and off he went 
on a course that led to his execution 
my husband said in a situation like this one cannot place 
ones family over the needs of an entire nation said his widow 
now judith gyenes 
maleter was executed in 1958 for his role in the failed revolt 
against soviet domination along with the defiant premier imre nagy 
and others the executions were carried out in secret and announced 
later without elaboration unofficial reports at the time said they 
were hanged 
now after 30 years in the course of renewed attempts at 
wideranging political reforms the leaders of the 1956 uprising 
held in disgrace by the communists are reemerging in the official 
consciousness as pioneers of reform 
for three decades ms gyenes and other relatives of the revolts 
leaders have fought for their official recognition as patriots 
rather than counterrevolutionaries 
the communist party leadership at a meeting in february 
partially reassessed its evaluation of the 1956 events as a 
counterrevolution acknowledging that it also bore elements of a 
popular uprising 
as the communist partys ideologist janos berecz had said 
recently that political rehabilitation of the 1956 leaders is under 
way with publication of three books on nagy and the revolt on 
wednesday berecz was one of four conservatives removed from the 
politburo in a move that appears to strengthen party leaders who 
favor introducing a multiparty system 
the relatives also have been given official permission to rebury 
their loved ones in marked graves 
the bodies of nagy maleter and three others have been exhumed 
from unmarked graves in plot no 301 of budapests sprawling 
rakoskeresztur cemetery the funeral is set for june 16 the 
anniversary of nagys execution 
nevertheless maleters widow says the government still has a 
long way to go to face up to the tragedy of the 1956 revolt 
i dont think the authorities have come to the stage where 
they can confront the whole nature of this and see it for the 
travesty of justice that it was she said in an interview in 
budapest where she is a librarian 
according to western estimates as many as 30000 people died in 
the uprising which began oct 23 1956 and was brought to a 
bloody end by soviet troops and tanks nov 4 
ms gyenes now 55 and remarried remembers the last time she 
saw her maleter as a free man 
it was nov 3 1956 and he had just been named nagys defense 
minister and was appointed to head the hungarian delegation to 
negotiate with kremlin emissaries on the withdrawal of soviet 
troops 
nagy had declared hungary a neutral country and withdrew it from 
the sovietled warsaw pact military alliance 
my husband was optimistic ms gyenes said but she added 
that she was extremely upset that he was going to a soviet military 
base for the negotiations with the kremlin officials 
the next day maleter and his entire delegation were under 
soviet arrest 
two years later nagy maleter and an estimated 2000 others were 
executed 
ms gyenes was allowed to see her imprisoned husband only twice 
before his death and received just two letters from him they had 
no children 
this whole episode was one of the most infamous occurrences in 
hungarian history she said 
when the revolt broke out maleter commanded a column of 
hungarian tanks that rushed to budapests kilian barracks to defend 
it against rebels but after speaking to some of them he joined 
the revolt and announced he was turning the barracks over to the 
revolutionaries a key factor in solidifying popular support for 
the uprising 
ms gyenes said an enormous crowd gathered to hear maleter speak 
at the barracks 
i was amazed that this unknown military man all of a sudden 
was a popular hero she said 
a leading communist reformer in todays hungary imre pozsgay 
has said the national consensus needed to overcome the countrys 
current problems can only be achieved by clearing up the past 
maleters widow agrees 
it is my conviction that until justice is served there is 
no way we can speak of any kind of consensus or a new social 
contract she said 
