<TEXT>
a powerful concentration of hydrogen peroxide 
being promoted as a treatment for aids and cancer has caused the 
death of a texas child who mistook the chemical for water the food 
and drug administration said thursday 
the fda said the death occurred in conroe texas last september 
when a mother took what she thought was a bottle of water from her 
refrigerator and poured drinks for her two children and the child 
of a neighbor 
the neighbors child died and the two others were severely 
injured 
the fda announcement also said that two brothers in dennison 
texas were hospitalized after a similar incident the fda did not 
reveal the names of those injured or killed 
a product sold as 35 percent food grade hydrogen peroxide to 
be used in what is called hyperoxygenation therapy for aids 
cancer and more than 60 other conditions was blamed for the death 
and injuries the fda said 
the agency said the peroxide solution is highly corrosive and is 
considered dangerous the peroxide concentration is about 10 times 
stronger than the 3 percent solution commonly used to disinfect 
minor cuts 
this concentration is not approved by the fda for any 
therapeutic purpose said fda commissioner frank e young no 
one has come forward with any evidence this substance taken 
internally has any medical value buyers are being cheated and 
subjected to significant risks and family members are being 
injured 
the fda said the concentrated hydrogen peroxide is purchased 
from chemical plants in texas and mexico repackaged in smaller 
containers and then sold under such labels as biowater and 
h202 
literature accompanying the product explains how to dilute the 
peroxide and claims that it can be used for sprouting seeds 
purifying meat and for treatment of acne gum disease athletes 
foot colic headache varicose veins acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome and cancer 
use of the product is promoted as an alternative medicine by 
mailorder distributors in texas wisconsin minnesota and 
california and by some health food outlets the fda said it is 
sold in pint quart and gallon containers some with 
childresistant caps 
the fda said material distributed with the peroxide includes 
fictitious medical claims and claims that the benefits of the 
chemical are being suppressed by the government and the medical 
establishment 
federal officials have attempted to block promotion of the 
chemical as a home remedy since 1985 but it has continued the fda 
announcement said 
