products for power of failing to abide by a 1987 settlement 
agreement in which the company allegedly said it would pay 75000 
in fines and stop selling the replacement pipes 
despite the widespread misperception that these pipes will 
improve vehicle performance they are merely lengths of plain 
exhaust tubing cut to fit in place of catalytic converters and 
offer no performance advantages over properly functioning catalytic 
converters said the epa 
the pipes dramatically increase emissions of 
healththreatening pollutants by releasing untreated exhaust 
gases said don clay acting epa assistant administrator for air 
and radiation 
the action filed in federal court asks that the company pay 
135000 in civil penalties for failing to comply with the 1987 
agreement and 2500 in additional penalties per day that it was in 
noncompliance the overall fine would exceed 14 million the 
agency said 
