<TEXT>
the federal government has made it too 
difficult for states to use medicaid to pay for home care services 
for the poor according to six senators who introduced a measure 
thursday designed to remedy the situation 
the legislation is aimed at thousands of medicaid beneficiaries 
who need help with their home routines but whose sickness or 
frailty is not severe enough to require them to enter a nursing 
home 
the bill designed to cut through red tape to make it easier for 
states to pay for at least part of the cost of home care under 
medicaid was unveiled at a news conference by its author sen jay 
rockefeller dwva the cosponsors are sens john heinz rpa 
paul simon dill george mitchell dmaine bill bradley dnj 
and david pryor dark 
in 1981 the government approved interim regulations authorizing 
states to get waivers to pay for home care under medicaid a 
federal program providing medical services to the needy 
the regulations specify that such care can be provided in the 
homes using medicaid funds only if it saves money over hospital or 
nursing home care 
the bill estimated to cost 680 million over the first five 
years would end the waiver system and make home care services an 
optional statewide benefit 
</TEXT>
