immediate import restrictions have been 
ordered on eggs from countries where a food poisoning organism 
salmonella enteritidis has been found in poultry the agriculture 
department said thursday 
the organism also known as phagetype 4 bacterium has not been 
detected in the united states or canada said larry b slagle 
acting administrator of the departments animal and plant health 
inspection service 
but it has recently been identified as the cause of numerous 
outbreaks of salmonellosis in poultry in some areas of europe 
including the balkan countries and the iberian peninsula he said 
it has become the major sources of salmonellosis food 
poisoning in humans in england and wales slagle said it is 
known to be spread by poultry and poultry products including 
eggs 
ma mixson another agency official said he had no estimate of 
how many countries will be affected in any case he said 
relatively few eggs are imported into the united states so the 
us restrictions will have little impact 
in humans slagle said the salmonella bacteria can cause 
stomach cramps diarrhea fever and sometimes nausea and vomiting 
from five to 72 hours after they eat contaminated food 
slagle said the usda agency restrictions mean that eggs may be 
imported only if they meet certain conditions to ensure that they 
are free of diseases and if they are accompanied by a certificate 
which identifies the flock and country of origin the ports of 
embarkation and arrival and the name and address of the exporter 
and importer 
