president bush has selected eddie brown the 
first indian to head a major state agency in arizona to oversee 
the operation of the troubleplagued bureau of indian affairs the 
white house announced thursday 
brown the former director of the arizona department of economic 
security and a member of the pascua yaqui tribe will be nominated 
as assistant secretary for indian affairs at the interior 
department 
interior secretary manuel lujan said brown has a broad 
background in intergovernmental relations with native americans 
as well as prior experience with the bureau where he was a 
division chief in 1985 
as the top interior department official specifically in charge 
of indian affairs brown will oversee an agency that has been the 
subject of sharp congressional criticism in recent months because 
of alleged improprieties involving the bia and other indian matters 
eddie will make an excellent assistant secretary sen john 
mccain rariz said in a statement i can think of no one more 
highly qualified for the bia spot and i commend this appointment 
very highly 
however the arizona senates republican leader john mawhinney 
of tucson had a mixed view if the job calls for somebody with 
an extraordinary understanding of assorted indian tribes then 
hes an excellent choice but if theyre looking for someone with 
very strong managerial and supervisory skills i think theyve got 
the wrong man 
brown 43 drew praise during six years as an assistant director 
of the states department of economic security for reshaping the 
states contractual relations with tribal governments in what 
became a national model he also won respect of indian leaders and 
federal officials as director of the bias socialservices division 
in 1985 and 1986 
but appointed the head of the arizona department in january 
1987 by thengov evan mecham he ran into complaints from 
legislators and others that he was in over his head as the top man 
complaints concerned delayed payments to vendors and delayed 
services to department clients and costly mixups in how state and 
federal funds were used one delay lost the department 44 million 
in federal funds 
the bia is the arm of the interior department that oversees 
indian welfare education natural resources and economic growth 
its programs and policies affect more than 14 milion indians and 
alaska natives 
the position of bia commisioner is vacant and brown as 
assistant secretary for indian affairs will oversee the bureaus 
operations 
the bia has been under sharp criticism in congress where a 
senate select committee has held a series of hearings that 
disclosed cases of fraud mafia infiltration and child sexual 
abuses on indian reservations under the eyes of the federal agency 
mccain and other senators including sen dennis deconcini 
dariz who have been involved in the hearings have said the 
findings make clear the bureau is in need of major overhaul 
the bia has been grossly negligent in protecting the resource 
that american indians care about most deeply their families 
deconcini said after the conclusion of the recent set of hearings 
in february which included one session about sexual abuse among 
indian children 
