<TEXT>
two graduate students said thursday they had 
detected indications of cold fusion in an experiment conducted with 
heavy water but they could not get the same results using ordinary 
water 
van l eden and wei liu physics students at the university of 
washington said they did not duplicate exactly the highly 
publicized experiment by university of utah chemist b stanley pons 
and martin fleischmann of englands university of southampton 
pons and fleischmann said they apparently produced nuclear 
fusion in a tabletop experiment using ordinary lab equipment 
but eden 28 and liu 27 said they did get indications that 
fusion may have taken place in their experiment last week 
in the experiment a mass spectrometer detected a possible 
indicator of tritium a radioactive isotope of hydrogen commonly 
produced in fusion reactions 
the indicator was found when the experiment was run using 
deuterium a hydrogen isotope and component of deuterium oxide or 
heavy water eden said the indicator was not detected when the 
test was repeated with ordinary water 
the students results if confirmed could help answer a 
question raised about the utah experiment by harold furth director 
of plasma physics at princeton university 
furth at a meeting wednesday of the american chemical society 
in dallas said that some experts believe the energy detected in 
the utah experiment is actually a chemical reaction that is not 
understood 
but he said if the experiment worked using deuterium oxide but 
not ordinary water it would suggest the reaction actually did 
involve some sort of deuterium fusion 
the students said however that they did not detect the 
substantial quantities of neutrons expected from a fusion reaction 
although they were not using a particularly sensitive detector for 
them 
for their experiment the pair used a test tube containing 
deuterium oxide in which a palladium electrode and gold wire were 
placed and connected to a power source the palladium electrode was 
connected to a vacuum chamber which in turn was connected to the 
mass spectrometer which detects nuclear particles 
pons and fleischman used a platinum wire instead of gold and 
observed the amount of excess heat produced rather than observing 
tritium particles 
eden and liu cautioned that their results were preliminary and 
needed review by other scientists they also said they had not 
ruled out other explanations for what was observed 
researchers at brigham young university texas aampm georgia tech 
and moscow university in the soviet union also have found possible 
indications of cold fusion but said their findings need further 
testing 
fusion the energy process that powers the sun and the hydrogen 
bomb has been touted as the ultimate energy source if a means 
could be found to produce it economically 
the two students said their major outofpocket expense was for 
about three pizzas bought by liu 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

