government lawyer kristina nygaard says she generally carries a 
briefcase home and spends a few hours after supper with papers 
spread out on the dining room table working on hydroelectric plant 
licenses for the federal energy regulatory commission 
in this company town theres a lot of voluntary unpaid 
overtime exceptions can be found of course but many of the 
political appointees and highlevel careerists the people who 
really run the government are a hardworking bunch 
often a package of crackers and a soft drink at the desk serves 
as lunch and the real work gets done at the tail end of the day 
that flies in the face of the stereotype of bureaucrats as 
surly officious paper shufflers just putting in their time in 
fact some research finds that most americans are actually 
satisfied with their facetoface contacts with government workers 
most government people like workers everywhere do a days 
work then leave at quitting time government personnel officials 
say they are about as productive as other workers 
but closer to the top among the 5000 or so senior executives 
of government are many who are on the job early and late 
helmut hellwig who is with the national institute of standards 
and technology says he leaves home at 630 am leaves work at 
730 pm and when he goes in on weekends to put in a few quiet 
hours he is rarely the only one to show up 
another government worker is harry a blackmun 80 associate 
justice of the supreme court 
hear him describe his work habits the job for me is really 
seven days a week you can say my average work week exceeds 60 
hours its a rare saturday that i miss coming to the court i 
try to avoid coming in on sundays but i will work at home 
on saturdays the president may be at camp david but hundreds 
of his minions are laboring away 
like many agencies the irs requires employees to sign in if 
they enter the building during weekends signin sheets show that 
on average 500 people put in some extra time at their desks on 
saturdays and about the same number on sundays in all 6300 
people work at irs headquarters 
last fall when 45 million copies of your federal income 
taxes were printed irs people involved in its preparation 
travelled to the printing plant in new jersey worked weekends and 
even through thanksgiving reports the agencys public affairs 
director ellen murphy 
its hard to generalize but i would certainly say government 
people are very hard workers says business executive alan 
campbell who ran the office of personnel management in the carter 
administration 
adds donald devine who held that job under president reagan 
at the top of government by and large people work harder than 
they do in the private sector he says the work culture 
varies from one agency to another with the hardest working people 
in his view found at the pentagon and other defenserelated 
agencies and at the irs fbi and customs service 
one reason the day is so long for government executives 
meetings the boss his deputies and his agency heads spend much of 
their time in meetings that leaves the end of the day for reading 
the mail returning phone calls thinking about tomorrow and if 
theres time about the big picture 
mark a abramson who runs the center for excellence in 
government which is sort of an alumni association of 400 
exgovernment executives is a student of the subject 
in government he says there are more people you have to 
get agreement from you cant do anything unilaterally there are 
so many actors and so many bases to get touched the first time you 
forget to call an interest group and tell them what youre planning 
to do you get creamed 
once a policy emerges from all those meetings it has to be sold 
within the agency to the chief to other agencies that will be 
affected to the budget people to congress and to the interested 
publics more meetings 
moreover the person going to all those meetings must still 
manage his own little bureaucracy he has to get the staffs input 
before a meeting then brief the staff afterward so all march in 
the same direction 
political people often talk about their input i work 16 
hours a day i work 17 and weekends because there is no bottom 
line no profit or loss in government so they cant talk about 
their output says abramson 
on capitol hill congressional aides often young single and 
dedicated work long hours and then walk down the block to the hawk 
amp dove bullfeathers the tune inn or some such place to spend half 
the night socializing with the very same people they spent their 
day with and talking about what else work 
ask officialdom about work habits and joseph califanos name is 
likely to pop up when he ran the department of health education 
and welfare under president carter he was a legendary workaholic 
despite carters admonition to aides that he didnt want government 
to keep them from being good family men and women 
califano was famous for calling a staff meeting for 7 pm 
which might not get started until 8 or 9 and not end before 11 
he was a harddriving guy who wanted to do a lot and do it 
quickly and who expected people to be available when he wanted 
them recalls dan marcus califanos deputy general counsel 
califano installed lights on assistants phones to summon them 
right away now 
in those kinds of positions the responsibilities are heady 
the issues are interesting and you usually would come into those 
jobs with a fairly high level of enthusiasm and drive says 
marcus 
</TEXT>
