fw woolworth cos board of directors has 
approved a new corporate structure that the giant retailer said was 
aimed at making itself more responsive to business opportunities 
under the plan which must be approved by stockholders 
woolworth would become a wholly owned subsidiary of a new holding 
entity called woolworth corp 
the company believes the new holding company arrangement would 
more accurately reflect the companys current management 
structure woolworth said wednesday in a statement 
additionally it would increase organizational operational 
and financial flexibility and allow woolworth corp to more 
effectively take advantage of future business opportunities the 
company stated 
the company did not elaborate on why the board took the action 
or what future business opportunities might be contemplated 
woolworth spokeman jf carroll said the company would confine its 
comments to the written announcement 
the plan to be presented to stockholders at an annual meeting 
in universal city calif on june 22 calls for outstanding shares 
of woolworths common and series a preferred stock to be 
automatically exchanged for equal holdings of the new woolworth 
corp which would be based in new york 
retail industry analysts said they were unable to determine the 
significance of woolworths move given that the new arrangement 
apparently would not alter the companys ownership in any 
meaningful way 
woolworths shares closed at 5150 in new york stock exchange 
consolidated trading up 150 
woolworth said that if the plan is approved each share in 
woolworth corp would represent the same interest in the same 
business and assets operated under the same management as did a 
share of the company immediately prior to the share exchange 
to bolster their abilities to defend themselves against unwanted 
takeover attempts numerous companies have realigned their 
corporate structures some adopting employee stock owernship plans 
esops to place a bigger portion of their shares in friendly hands 
last year woolworth attracted the interest of the corporate 
raiding haft family 
a partnership controlled by dart group corps chairman herbert 
haft last spring disclosed plans to acquire 15 million or more of 
the retailers stock 
haft and his son robert have become known as corporate raiders 
because on repeated occasions they have purchased stakes in 
companies made unsuccessful takeover bids and then profited by 
selling their stock when the companies have repurchased the shares 
or gone private in buyouts 
several analysts said they were unaware of any renewed takeover 
interest in woolworth lately nor have they heard speculation about 
