millions of cars and trucks are recalled 
annually when they roll into dealerships dollars follow 
its profitable for the dealership to do the recalls said 
bill schmirl service manager at doan ford in rochester ny 
theres markup on parts and labor 
service managers eyes lit up earlier this week when ford motor 
co asked car and truck owners to return more than 340000 vehicles 
to fix a variety of safetyrelated and other problems 
the recalls involved suspension problems in trucks a seat belt 
bolt in new luxury cars potential electric troubles in some 1988 
model cars and trucks and cracked and discolored leather 
upholstery in a car ford imports from west germany 
the national highway traffic safety administration said about 
42 million vehicles were recalled in 1988 for safetyrelated 
problems the environmental protection agency said 33 million were 
recalled for emission system problems in addition automakers 
independently issued recalls for other reasons 
for dealers service departments each vehicle brought back for 
the free repairs means profits on parts and labor costs borne by 
the manufacturer 
it is a good time to sell service said bill heitritter 
service manager at crescent chevroletgeo in des moines iowa it 
helps the dealer because its a selling thing 
we process about 2000 to 3000 recalls a year he said 
its a priority thing for us 
automakers declined to say how much they spend on recalls 
annually regardless of the expense ford spokesman chuck snearly 
said paying for recall repairs is just good business 
its considerably less than the cost of a lawsuit and the 
disloyalty of an owner down the road he said people dont 
mind having a problem when its fixed for free what will get you 
into trouble is if you have a problem and you dont respond to 
people 
general motors corp spokesman dave hudgens added that 
research shows that customers want to hear from the manufacturer 
when there is a safety concern 
automakers learn of possible problems from various sources 
including assembly line workers drivers at proving grounds 
consumer groups and government agencies 
after investigating a manufacturer will decide whether to issue 
a recall on its own the federal highway safety organization and 
the epa can order recalls but most are made by automakers 
sometimes with government prodding 
notifying owners is a tough job in a country that lives on 
wheels automakers often consult rl polk amp co in detroit which 
monitors us vehicle registrations to find who owns a vehicle 
being recalled 
we continue to follow up and send letters wave after wave of 
letters until we get a completion rate as high as we could get 
fords snearly said 
that ranges from nearly 100 percent for a new car to 75 percent 
for a 5yearold vehicle older cars or those that have changed 
hands are harder to find 
problems appearing more serious to consumers such as possible 
steering failure typically get a higher initial response rate 
than problems that seem less critical such as an emissions system 
leak 
depending on the trouble customers may wait to have recall work 
performed until their vehicle is due for routine maintenance or 
until something else goes wrong sometimes recalls are simply 
ignored 
the automakers maintain they are clear of liability for defects 
once a good faith attempt is made to find the owner of a recalled 
car 
some dealers routinely check for pending recalls when cars 
arrive to be serviced 
ford said that occurred recently during the american pony 
drive a caravan of ford mustangs brought to the united states by 
their european owners in connection with the models 25th 
anniversary 
