<TEXT>
a federal judge has dismissed charges against 
penny stock mogul meyer blinder his son and his brokerage and 
chastised the securities and exchange commission for misconduct in 
a 1983 civil case 
us district judge lewis babcock on wednesday ordered that no 
documents or testimony obtained in the case could ever again be 
used by the sec in court against blinder his son larry and 
blinder robinson amp co 
the judge awarded attorney fees to blinder 
blinder robinson amp co was accused of not keeping correct books 
and records required by the sec when securities are traded the sec 
had sought an immediate injunction against the firm but a federal 
judge ordered a trial 
blinder attorney philip lowery said the brokerage was going from 
a manual system to a computer system in 1983 when the sec said the 
books were out of date 
the court found that in pretrial actions the sec had failed to 
comply with a court order and had not acted in good faith 
robert davenport sec regional administrator in denver said he 
could not recall such a sanction being imposed on the sec which 
has 60 days appeal 
in february the us supreme court rejected blinders challenge 
to the secs power to crack down on fraud stemming from 1980 sec 
sanctions restricting his activities 
blinder began his business in westbury long island and moved 
its headquarters to denver in the late 1970s it became one of the 
nations leading underwriters of penny stocks or lowpriced 
securities 
the sec in 1980 accused blinder and the firm of deceiving 
investors in underwriting a 25 million sale of stock in american 
leisure corp intended to finance construction and operation of a 
casino hotel in atlantic city nj 
a federal judge in denver ruled in 1982 the firm defrauded 
investors by withholding important information and barred blinder 
and his firm from engaging in similar practices 
