conagra inc said thursday it has agreed to 
divest a portion of holly farms corps flour milling operation if 
it succeeds in a 1 billion buyout of its poultryindustry 
competitor 
the agreement with the staff of the federal trade commission 
would require conagra to divest 24 million pounds of holly farms 
daily flour milling capacity if the merger is completed conagra 
spokesman walt casey said 
in return the ftc staff will not recommend commission action to 
block the merger casey said 
the agreement requires divestiture within 15 months after the 
ftc consent decree process which should take about 10 weeks 
until the divestiture is complete the holly farms flour milling 
business will be held separate from conagra and operated 
independently conagra said 
holly farms of memphis tenn has a total flour milling 
capacity of 55 million pounds a day while conagras capacity is 
26 million pounds casey said 
conagra has been locked in a bitter fight with tyson foods of 
springdale ark over the poultry producer 
in a hostile bid tyson offered 6350 a share or a total of 
115 billion for holly farms conagra has offered a stock 
exchange valued at about 107 billion 
holly farms stockholders were scheduled to vote on the merger 
proposals friday a conagra vote was scheduled for later that day 
