a former merrill lynch stockbroker 
convicted in an insider trading scandal was sentenced thursday to 
six months in prison to be served concurrently with an identical 
sentence on a separate charge in new york 
us district judge ellen burns said she took into account 
william dillons continuing cooperation with investigators in 
deciding not to add to the sentence imposed tuesday by a federal 
judge in new york 
dillon 34 of old lyme pleaded guilty last year in new haven 
and new york to single counts of wire fraud stemming from a scheme 
in which he illicitly obtained advance copies of business week 
magazine 
while working as a broker at merrill lynch amp cos new london 
office dillon profited by trading stocks that received favorable 
mention in the magazines inside wall street column he sold 
the stocks after the magazine was released to the public and their 
prices rose 
a federal judge in new york sentenced dillon to two years in 
prison but suspended all but six months the judge also placed 
dillon on three years probation required him to perform 200 hours 
of community service and ordered him to make full restitution of an 
amount to be determined by the securities and exchange commission 
the government contends dillon made 118000 in profits through 
his illegal scheme between may 1986 and july 1988 
burns said there was no need for her to order restitution or 
community service because the new york sentence took care of that 
prosecutors had also recommended a concurrent sentence 
dillon has been working since january as a carpenter helping to 
renovate homes for the retarded his attorney henry putzel told 
the court 
he will not have to surrender until june 5 
dillon paid 10 to 30 for advance copies of business week to 
various employees of rr donnelley amp sons co which prints the 
weekly publication at two plants several donnelley employees were 
fired in the wake of the scandal 
dillons mother elizabeth baird maintained an account through 
which some trades were made based on the information from business 
week the government said she was not charged but has been 
required to turn over any profits she realized 
dillon also has admitted tipping off others to the information 
he obtained 
assistant us attorney peter jongbloed said an investigation is 
continuing but declined any other comment 
