a former chicago board of trade floor broker 
alleges in a lawsuit that he was fired by a division of merrill 
lynch for blowing the whistle on what he said was a scheme that 
cost the exchange millions of dollars 
but a merrill lynch spokesman in new york said thursday the 
allegations of the scheme and the improper firing are totally 
without foundation 
james e zechman a former 500000ayear vice president for 
merrill lynch pierce fenner amp smith inc said he was fired after 
he told his bosses the company was disguising outside customer 
trades as house trades to avoid higher exchange fees 
merrill lynch knowingly created and perpetuated a scheme 
and improperly deprived the cbot of millions of dollars in 
revenues zechman charged in the suit 
zechmans allegation of wrongdoing by merrill lynch is totally 
without foundation fred yager a company spokesman said in a 
statement zechmans termination in august 1988 was based solely 
on his own personal misconduct at no time did he bring any 
allegations of wrondoing to merrill lynchs attention 
according to the suit the board of trade charges 4 cents for 
each trade that member firms such as merrill lynch make for their 
own accounts it charges a 1 fee for each transaction member firms 
conduct for nonmember firms and individual investors 
the nonmember pays the 1 fee to merrill lynch which pays the 
exchange 
zechmans suit charges that merrill lynch funneled nonmember 
trades through its house account thus paying only 4 cents to the 
exchange however the suit charges merrill lynch billed customers 
the 1 but called it a risk profile fee to hide the scheme from 
the exchange 
